<exercises><title> <em>Check your Understanding</em> </title>
	<p>
		<exercise><title> <em>Answer-the-Following</em> </title>
			
			<task label="chkpt-identifying-lhcc-1"><title> Identifying Homogeneous Equations </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Which of the following equations is homogeneous?
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices>
					<choice>
						<statement> <m>\ds\quad y'' + 4y^2 = 0 </m> </statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. This equation looks homogeneous, but homogeneity only applies to linear equations.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement> <m>\ds\quad y'' + 4y' + 3y = 7 </m> </statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The equation has a non-zero constant term, making it non-homogeneous.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement> <m>\ds\quad y' + 2y = x^2 </m> </statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The right-hand side has a non-zero function of <m>x</m>, so this is non-homogeneous.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement> <m>\ds\quad y'' + 4y' + 3y = 0 </m> </statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct! This equation has no constant term and is homogeneous.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<task label="chkpt-identifying-lhcc-2"><title> Identifying Constant Coefficients </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Select all equations that have constant coefficients.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<choices>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad y'' - 4y' + 7y = 0 </m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct! All coefficients are constant.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad x^2 y'' + x y' - y = 0 </m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The coefficient of <m> y'' </m> is <m> x^2 </m>, which is not constant.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice correct="yes">
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad y''' - 2y' + 3y = 0 </m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Correct! All coefficients are constant.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
					<choice>
						<statement>
							<p>
								<m>\quad e^x y'' + y' + y = 0 </m>
							</p>
						</statement>
						<feedback>
							<p>
								Incorrect. The coefficient <m> e^x </m> is not a constant.
							</p>
						</feedback>
					</choice>
				</choices>
			</task>

			<task label="chkpt-identifying-lhcc-3"><title> Matching Equations with Properties </title>
				<statement>
					<p>
						Match each differential equation to its correct classification.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						Good work! Recognizing equation types helps determine the best solution method.
					</p>
				</feedback>
				<matches>
					<match>
						<premise><m> y'' + y' + y = 0 </m></premise>
						<response>LHCC Equation</response>
					</match>
					<match>
						<premise><m> y y' + y'' = 0 </m></premise>
						<response>Nonlinear Equation</response>
					</match>
					<match>
						<premise><m> y'' + \ln x \cdot y = 0 </m></premise>
						<response>Linear, Variable Coefficients</response>
					</match>
				</matches>
			</task>

			<task label="chkpt-identifying-lhcc-4"><title> Structure of LHCC Equations </title>
				<statement correct="yes">
					<p>
						A second-order LHCC equation has the general form
						<me>
							a_2 y'' + a_1 y' + a_0 y = 0
						</me>,
						where <m> a_2, a_1, a_0 </m> are constants.
					</p>
				</statement>
				<feedback>
					<p>
						Correct! LHCC equations have constant coefficients and no nonhomogeneous terms.
					</p>
				</feedback>
			</task>

		</exercise>
	</p>
</exercises>